Still working on the last chapter of the current act of a story of which I've recently returned. Thankfully I have time to get it sorted before it's needed for uploading, because it's taking longer than writing this and the previous chapters first draft combined.
See, I had it completed, but unedited. Then, as I finished editing the penultimate chapter, realised that I had cut a bunch of moments which I couldn't find a place for in the first draft, only to have an epiphany which let me fit most of them in for a much more exciting (or I hope more exciting) finale to the act.
The problem is it's pretty much rewriting the whole thing from the ground up, yet I keep finding myself rechecking what I'd written for other moments that I could potentially still use and otherwise having some regrets over getting rid of what I'd written. It was good, but this other stuff seems better.
It's a big weakness of mine; I find full rewrites very draining. Editing and fleshing out or trimming parts are fine, but deleting so much stuff which I had a passion to write just hurts I guess.

The days I'm worst I was cooped up all day and didn't eat a real meal (No, ramen with canned chicken is not a a real meal)

For you, go make a chicken-spinach pasta with a creamy garlic sauce.
All you need is a noodle of choice, chicken (any cut, canned or fresh will do), spinach, cream, flour, milk, butter, dried herbs and garlic (fresh, minced, or powdered will do)

First make a roux from butter and flour, then add cream and garlic. Cut with milk until you've reached double what you think you'll need.
While the sauce simmers, boil your pasta.
Make you chicken into 3/4 inch (1 and half CM), put it on a skewer, and cook over medium-high heat until done. Season it as you like
In the same pan as the chicken bring down the heat to medium-low, add olive oil, garlic, salt, and pepper to taste. Once wilted, add the chicken-garlic pan to the now finished sauce, then serve atop noodles.
You can freeze the garlic-chicken-spinach sauce really easily and it reheats in the microwave, so don't be scared of bulk portions.

If that doesn't float your boat, I can offer you my gyro or pork butt and sloppy joe recipes
